{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8eb276d1-53eb-42be-8e34-04507b1aaa9a","content":"This is a known breaking change. In .NET 10 MAUI, Android defaults to **edge-to-edge** rendering, which makes `AdjustResize` ineffective. You now need to react to **window insets** to detect the keyboard and adjust your layout.\n\n### Quick fix — `AdjustPan`\n\nThe simplest option (may hide your message list header):\n\n```csharp\n// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs\n[Activity(... WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan)]\n```\n\n### Recommended fix — Keyboard insets listener\n\nFor a chat screen you'll want more control. Handle the IME insets in your `MainActivity`:\n\n```csharp\n// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(\n        Window!.DecorView,\n        new KeyboardInsetsListener());\n}\n\nprivate class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n{\n    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n        Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n    {\n        var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n        var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n        // Use whichever bottom inset is larger\n        int bottom = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom);\n        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);\n\n        return insets;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis listens for the software keyboard (IME) appearing/disappearing and pushes your content up by exactly the keyboard height — your input bar stays visible and your message list shrinks to fit.\n\n### iOS\n\nNo changes needed — iOS MAUI already adjusts for the keyboard automatically via safe area insets.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d50cfd44-9ef1-438d-82fc-c50a235a51f0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10.\n\nThis is a known change in .NET MAUI. In .NET 9 (and earlier), Android's `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was used, but that API was deprecated in Android 30+ and was removed/changed in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nLet me provide a concise, helpful answer about the current recommended approach for .NET 10 MAUI.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` is no longer viable since Android deprecated it at API 30. The better alternatives are using `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Pan` to shift the window up when the keyboard appears, or implementing the newer `WindowInsets` approach where you listen to keyboard height changes and adjust your layout padding dynamically. In .NET 10, Android's edge-to-edge display mode by default breaks the old `AdjustResize` behavior, so I need to handle keyboard insets manually using the `WindowInsets` API to detect when the IME appears and adjust padding accordingly. I'm setting up a platform-specific listener in the Android code to respond to these keyboard changes. Finishing the window insets listener implementation...\n\nThe listener calculates the maximum padding needed between the IME and system bars, then applies that to the view. Alternatively, there's a simpler `AdjustPan` approach, though for chat apps the insets method is preferable since `AdjustPan` just pans the whole window up and can hide your message history.","outputTokens":1610,"requestId":"3C37:7874F:AED6A6:DA1750:6A012C24"},"id":"049e20e0-dd8b-42f4-a100-a3337917dbac","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:09:21.657Z","parentId":"19b19359-5454-417f-9814-f569777d4f82"}
